Lars Huismann

Who is Lars Huismann?

Lars Huismann is a Berlin based techno producer.

Born in 1987 in Berlin, from a young age he had a passion for music, playing in jazz and metal bands when he was a teenager. He then transitioned to techno in the late 90s, when the techno scene in Berlin was booming. He was there when it all started!

Since the opening of his label LHR in 2015, we can really see the solidification of his sound and signature traits. His sound is characterized by this bigroom kick, rolling baseline and progressive beats resulting in the classic groove and hard groove techno that he is especially famous for.

Aim

I want to analyse his tracks and have a better idea of the patterns within them, mainly I want to understand how his sound has changed over the releases and where is he moving towards. This will also give a very good idea of where the whole groove and hard groove techno scene is moving towards as he is a renowned producer and many big DJs often play his tracks during their sets.

#Extracting all the tracks produced by Lars Huismann (LH) that are available on spotify, this retrieves 121 tracks.
LH <- get_artist_audio_features('lars huismann', include_groups = c("album", "single"))

Data Analysis

How busy has he been?

First I want to understand how many tracks Lars Huismann released per year.

#These are the packages I will need.
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

#Grouping the tracks per year of release.
tracks_per_year <- LH %>%
  group_by(album_release_year) %>%
  count()

# Using ggplot2 to create a bar chart
ggplot(tracks_per_year, aes(x = album_release_year, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Number of Tracks Released Per Year",
       x = "Release Year",
       y = "Number of Tracks")

Here we can see that in 2017 he released 26 tracks on Spotify which was the highest number of tracks he released in any given year.

During COVID19 he was probably very bored at home which allowed the time to produce a lot of tracks as well. And we see that post-COVID he hasnât released as many tracks.

Also we see that in 2015 there were no tracks released. That is probably because he was busy opening his label.

Happy or Sad Lars?

Letâs look at valance to see if Lars is a happy boi or a sad boi.

Valence shows how positive or negative a track is, on a scale of 0 to 1. The higher the number the more positive the tracks.

Positive tracks are happy, cheerful, and euphoric.

Negative tracks are sad, depressed, angry.

# Change album_name from character to factor before plotting
LH$album_release_year <- as.factor(LH$album_release_year)

#calculating the mean valance for his tracks
av_valance <- mean(LH$valence)

# Plot a boxplot
ggplot(LH, aes(x=album_release_year, y=valence))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = av_valance, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x="Album Release Year", y="Valence")

Here we can see that:

  1. There is quite some variability in valence between the tracks released each year. Meaning that for each year he has some songs that have a low valance and others have a high valence.

  2. In general his songs are considered to be negative since the average valance in close to 0.3.

  3. Lars must have been a bit depressed or sad between 2017 and 2021 because most of the released tracks were below the average valance which was already quite negative. However they have quite some variation within each year.

  4. 2023 was his most positive year because even the lowest quartile is almostas high as the average.

Lars is a very sad boi. But is he really?

I donât think so. I think it is hard to assess the happiness or sadness of techno because of the way the tracks are composed and structured. Many follow a 4x4 beat and are quite repetitive and sometime their elements or lack thereof can seem sad or depressed or angry but in fact create the opposite emotion to the listener.

Has he found his sound?

You see with a lot of techno producers that at the beginning of their production career they normally produce quite a variety of styles. It takes time for you to know what you like and develop your skills and your signature sound.

So letâs see if Lars has found his sound.

Energy

#Calculating the average energy 
av_energy <- mean(LH$energy)
print(av_energy)
[1] 0.9183388
ggplot(LH, aes(x=album_release_year, y=energy))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = av_energy, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x="Album Release Year", y="Energy")

Here we are looking at the energy level of the tracks released per year.

What does this tells us:

  1. Before 2021 there was quite some variation in energy levels, compared to 2021 and after. This tells me that Lars Huismann really honed in on his sound and found his niche place within the producers of techno. This because now he is producing tracks specifically for the club scene and to be mixed with 2 or more other tracks. This can be confirmed if we see low variability between other variables such as danceability.

  2. His last 3 years have produced some energetic tracks. This is my favorite period of his.

  3. In general most of his tracks are very energetic as he is a techno producer, with a mean energy level of 0.918.

My hypothesis

The hypothesis is that he honed in on his sound and found his niche spot within the techno producers.

To see if my hypothesis is true then lets look at danceability and see if the data per year has a low variability for the years 2021, 2022, 2023.

Danceability

Letâs see if danceability helps me prove or discard my hypothesis.

#Calculating the average danceability 
av_dance <- mean(LH$danceability)
print(av_dance)
[1] 0.6782314
ggplot(LH, aes(x=album_release_year, y=danceability))+
  geom_boxplot()+
   geom_hline(yintercept = av_dance, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x="Album Release Year", y="Dance")

Here we can see that:

  1. The variability seems to decrease as the years go on. You will always have some variability because all tracks are different.

  2. His average danceability score is 0.67 meaning his tracks are very danceable.

  3. Since 2018, there has been an increase in danceability between the tracks released.

  4. In the last 3 years (2021-2023), the danceability of the tracks was above average even when looking at the lower quartile.

This tells me that my hypothesis might be correct because Lars now has defined his concept of groove and danceability and is able to replicate in all the songs he releases.

It also tells me that he is really marketing his tracks to be played in clubs by djs and that they are not meant to be listened to individually but rather mixed with 2 or more tracks.

Time Signature

Time signature describes the compass or metric of the song. Techno producers almost always exclusively work with a 4x4 metric meaning there are 4 beats per compass.

This doesnât do much to prove my hypothesis but it is able to tell me whether or not Lats has been experimenting with counts or if he stuck to the golden rule.

#Calculating the average energy 
av_time_sig <- mean(LH$time_signature)
print(av_time_sig)
[1] 3.933884
ggplot(LH, aes(x=album_release_year, y=time_signature))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = av_time_sig, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x="Album Release Year", y="Time Signature")

Here we can see that only in 2014 there was some variation within the metrics used, meaning he was experimenting and probably what he was producing would not be considered techno but another genre of electronic music. For the rest he sticks to the golden rule of techno which is a 4x4 metric, although he has an out-liar every so often, meaning its not the norm, which is also demonstrated by the average time signature of 3.9.

Energy vs Danceability

First let me see if the increase in energy will lead to an increase in danceability.

#This is a data set with my top 5 songs from LH.
top5 <- LH |> filter(track_name %in% c("Cope", "Dusty Lick", "Sounds from the Past II", "Loucura", "Stroke"))
# Create a scatter plot
scatter_plot <- ggplot(LH, aes(x = energy, y = danceability, color = album_release_year)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, color = "grey") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, color = "grey") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = av_dance, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = av_energy, linetype = "dashed", color = "blue") +
  geom_text(data=top5, aes(label=track_name)) +
  labs(title = "Energy vs Danceability",
       x = "Energy",
       y = "Danceability")

# Print or display the plot
print(scatter_plot)

Here we can see that as energy increases so does danceability. Actually the danceability is quite varied when energy is lower, however as energy increases the variability decreases.

Here we can also see that my favorite tracks are mostly above both the averages of energy and danceability. This tells me that I like the songs that are fast, have a lot of energy and are quite danceable.
